<TITLE> UK's Nationwide raises mortgage rates again </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Nationwide, Britain's second-largest mortgage lender, is set to increase its fixed lending rates for new customers for the second time in two weeks, as it faces rising costs and heightened demand. Nationwide said it will raise the cost of its fixed-rate deals, passing on increases of between 12 and 32 basis points. The move follows a 20 basis point rise across its product range at the end of March. "Part of the reason for the increase is that the cost of borrowing for us has gone up," a Nationwide spokeswoman said. "But in addition, the effect of other lenders withdrawing from the market means we are seeing more applications, and we need to be able to maintain control on the amount of business the society is attracting." The building society said its base mortgage rate would drop in line with the Bank of England's 25 basis point interest rate cut on Thursday, offering some relief to British borrowers. Thousands of mortgage products have been withdrawn across the industry in recent months, as UK banks cut back amid a rise in funding costs and a housing market slowdo
